Sep 17 2009 	Uplifting views for tired room	The best part about this hotel is the view from the room. We stayed in the king bayview room, which had a view of the bay bridge and also alcatraz. The view was superb, especially when retiring on the day bed after a long day. The rooms itself, are showing a bit of wear and tear and are not particularly noteworthy. They have the same decor as other MO hotels, with touches of Asian flair; however, the furniture reminds you that this hotel has been around for at least a decade. The bathroom, while sizeable, includes sparse amenities, and the bizarre mini-tiled shower stall was reminscent of a gym shower and not a nice one. The service was good and consistent with other MO hotels; however, the early AM check out staff took a ridiculously long time to rectify our bill after a few hiccups. Like many others have mentioned, the location is very convenient, a short walking distance to Union Square or the Ferry Building.We booked a California residents rate off the hotel website, which was inclusive of parking. I would not have been happy paying the exorbitant overnight parking fee otherwise. The next time I go to SF, I will likely try a newer, more modern hotel despite the location, good service and nice views.	
Sep 4 2009	Elegant Asian aesthetic fantastic views	Flew up to San Francisco for a quick 2 night stay with 2 simple objectives: 1) to see the Georgia O'Keeffe/Ansel Adams and Richard Avedon exhibits at the SFMOMA, and 2) to sample the many culinary offerings at the Ferry Building. Both the museum and Ferry Building are near Market St., as are several BART subway stops (we would be car-less, taking BART from the airport, SFO, into the city). In the past, we have had memorable stays at the St. Regis, Ritz Carlton, Palace, and Campton Place. All except the Ritz are close to Market St., all except Campton Place have indoor pools. Online, I discovered an enticing California resident weekend rate for the Mandarin Oriental. We have stayed at Mandarins in Hong Kong and New York and think it is a luxurious collection of properties with an elegant Asian aesthetic, so we decided to book here. Of course, we had heard about the Mandarin's vaunted views.The Mandarin is located in the Financial District, 2 blocks north of Market St. This is a very quiet area on weekends--even McDonald's and Starbucks are closed--but more active areas like Union Square and the aforementioned Ferry Building and Market/SOMA are within easy walking distances. The hotel occupies the top 11 floors (38-48) of the 3rd tallest building in San Francisco, so yes, the views are fantastic. The lobby, restaurant, lounge, meeting rooms, well-equipped business center and small fitness center are on the floors 1-4. There is no pool or spa, but guests have access to these at a fitness club across the street. The floors housing the guest rooms are dumbbell-shaped with about 7 rooms at each octagonal end separated by a &quot;skybridge&quot; corridor with windows overlooking the bay and city. The 38th floor has 2 suites with large terraces replacing the skybridge.Our reservation was for a city view king, but I noticed online the price point of a bay view queen, with the same square footage, was often identical, so we requested and were given this room type. I thought it well worth it to sacrifice a larger bed for a better view. The bay view extended from the Golden Gate Bridge to Alcatraz, the Transamerica building, Coit Tower, almost to the Bay Bridge. An insulated wicker basket with jasmine tea and almond cookies is delivered shortly after you arrive in your room. The room was beautiful, far from a simple box shape with few 90 degree angles. The sheer shades on the window are elegantly embroidered. The MO channel on the flat screen TV is fun to watch, quite imaginative. There were 2 clocks--one a standard gold alarm clock, the other a fancier clock/CD player whose alarm I couldn't figure out. There is a DVD player and large closet. We had to request slippers.The bathroom was fairly large with 2 types of marble, although the counter space around the single sink was not ample. There was a wall clock whose loud ticking could be heard in the bedroom. The separate stall shower also was large but its tiles reminded me of a locker room. The toiletries and towels were a bit disappointing--the towels neither large nor plush, the toiletries small (1 fluid ounce each). The bath soap was the same tiny size as the soap for the sink.Overall, this was a great short visit to a great city. The SFMOMA exhibits were worthwhile, and although we missed the Farmer's Market at the Ferry Building, we were able to gorge ourselves at Taylor's Automatic Refresher, Mijita, the Slanted Door, and Hog Island Oyster Co., plus Sear's Fine Foods by Union Square. We wanted to try the renowned Dottie's True Blue Cafe in the Tenderloin, but the line was too long.The Mandarin is yet another worthy luxury hotel to consider when visiting San Francisco.	
Sep 1 2009 	What a view!	I stayed for 3 nights in a king bayview room . The third night free promotion made it a little more affordable. Everything about the hotel was first class but the view of the bay from my 38th floor room was sensational. I don't know why they don't put that view on their website as it is not possible to resist it.The only drawback to this hotel is its location in the financial district. On weekends it is pretty quiet in the area ( not necessarily a bad thing) but unless you are a committed walker you are a bit removed from some of the more popular spots. It is about a 15 minute walk to the cable car turntable at Powell and Market, a 25 minute walk to the ballpark. It is actually only a 20-25 minute walk up Sansome to Fisherman's Wharf and no hill climbing on that route which was nice.We did all this walking without any problem but it takes a little more time.	
