Jan 6 2008 	You'll love the attention to detall at the Mandarin Oriental.	My husband and I recenlty stayed at the Mandarin Oriental in San Francisco. We have stayed at M.O. before in New York and fell in love with their attention to service. Upon arrival we were greeted warmly and offered complimentary tea service. We asked for early check in and were granted early check in at 11:00 a.m. We were greeted by hotel employees as we entered and exited the hotel. They were very warm and friendly and even greeting us by name. Our room had a wonderful view of the Golden Gate Bridge and the Coit Tower. We had our tea service in the afternoon after a day of shopping. The tea pot arrived in a large basket along with almond cookies. After we came back from dinner, cold water was waiting for us along with slippers next to our bed. We had a wonderful stay. My only issue was our neighbors who departed in the middle of the night. They were very loud and entered and exited their room several times before departure. The clock alarm also went off at 5:00 a.m. so I guess the last guest forgot to turn it off. I finally took the battery out since I couldn't figure out how to turn it off at 5:00 a.m. in the dark. Minus these few events which the hotel had no control of we had a great stay. I would advise that some local restaurants were closed when we arrived. I believe that since this is a business area that some small restaurants are closed on the weekends. This is not a big deal since you will want to experience the wonderful restaurants in other parts of the city especially Micheal Mina at the Westin St. Francis. Hands down my favorite restaurant. The attention to detail at this restaurant is amazing. The lobster pot pie is to die for. When we departed the hotel we were offered coffee to go.	
Jan 1 2008 	Superb views	We stayed here on the last night of our trip from New York (we drove across, via Seattle) as we decided that we deserved some luxury after all those middle-of-nowhere motels! We booked a Bridge to Bridge room which had a 180 degree view from the Golden Gate to the Oakland Bay Bridge, and it really was amazing! The hotel itself is in the business district but the area had quite a lot of parking which was a bonus. We decided to take full advantage of our room so didn't venture out into the surrounding area, however as we were there on a Sunday night everything seemed very quiet when we drove in. The ground floor reception area is nice, clean, modern and well decorated with a very polite reception staff who booked us in quickly and with no fuss. The ground floor has a nice bar/lounge area where they serve lovely cocktails, a great variety of wines and delicious (complimentary) snacks of nuts and olives. I have to admit that my one reservation about staying here was also the main reason for the stay - the height. The room was on the 42nd floor which gave it such beautiful and stunning views (from the large windows as well as the glass walled corridors) but also meant a long elevator ride, which for a claustrophobic was quite a daunting prospect. Thankfully, the elevators are large and airey and speed directly to the 40th floor (they don't stop before this as the first 39 floors are offices) so the experience was pretty painless! The rooms themselves are wonderful with large, comfortable beds and sparkling, well laid out bathrooms. We ordered room service and spent the evening eating incredible stone baked pizzas and drinking champage whilst admiring the view and it is an experience I would highly recommend. The complimentary binoculars were very much appreciated and came in handy for zooming in on Alcatraz and the Bridges. All in all, this a wonderful place to stay, it's extremely comfortable and whilst it may be a little more expensive than other places the views make it worth every single penny. I would definitley recommend the Bridge to Bridge room for a great night!	
