Jan 14 2006	lovely spot from which to see the city	We splashed out on the Mandarin for the last two nights of our vacation, in part based on the reviews on this site. The view made the room worthwhile (although we were &quot;only&quot; on the 39th floor, and discovered that taking the elevator up to the top floor yields some spectacular views from the corridor). But we were assuming (in retrospect, for no particular reason) that the room would be larger, and that there would be a more appealing hotel bar to enhance our Mandarin experience. The service was impeccable - the concierge was more than happy to research and answer my random questions. This is an expensive hotel - if on company expenses, it would be a no brainer to stay here. But if you're on your own dime, it's definitely a serious splurge, so don't spend it if you're going to think about it too much.	
Oct 23 2005	The best hotel in the USA	My wife and I spent 5 nights at the Mandarin Oriental, San Francisco during August this year (2005). We selected the hotel largely based on the review of this site and we were not disappointed.We had arranged for a town car to collect us from the airport through Virgin and this more than likely put us in a great mood as it was an excellent welcome to a fantastic city. The doorman was waiting to great us by name (we still haven't figured out how they knew who we were) and instantly made us feel like royalty. The check-in staff were so friendly, again using my name and making me feel valued as a customer (some will say at $500+ a night they should but you certainly get more than you pay for) and we were upgraded from the Bay to Bay view room we had booked to a suite with sunken bath in the window and much greater floor space. We were introduced to one of the concierge team who made reservations for us at a local restaurant after which we were escorted to our room.I believe that first impressions (certainly when it comes to hotels) count a lot and our first impression of the room was excellent. The room was light and airy and the views were breathtaking - on the days when the famous San Francisco fog took a break you could see for miles - our room had views of the Bay Bridge as well as the Transamerica Pyramid - we couldn't see the Golden Gate Bridge but this was shrouded in fog for the majority of our stay so no great loss (you will see it constantly when you are out and about on the multitude of tours available). The room was incredibly clean and tidy, a complimentary set of binoculars enhance the view and the tv is a decent size and hidden away in a cabinet - it could do with updating as many similar priced hotels have larger and flatter screens but we didn't come to watch tv!). The bed was incredibly comfortable, with more cushions and pillows than a soft furnishing store which all added to the sense of opulance and luxury. Also in the room were a selection of comfy chairs which were really handy after long walks taking in the sights. One of my favourite aspects of the suite was the bathroom - it was massive, luxurious and had one of the best hotel showers I have come across. The walk in shower had enough room for about six people (I haven't actually tested this statement!) and the power was excellent especially given the fact that we were on the 38th floor. Two Mandarin embroidered robes were provided - they were a little on the small side - as well as slippers. The toileteries were E'sporta which my wife advise me are very good, combined with some fab bath salts and a Bonsai tree next to the bath. Again the views from the bathroom and the sunken bath were breathtaking especially at night.We had a turn-down service every evening, the robes were laid out on the bed, water provided, relaxing music played and bedside mats and slippers placed at the side of the bed.The hotel gym is fine for a quick workout with plenty of cardio machines, free weights and fixed weight equipment. I was the only person using the gym for much of my stay - a bonus of visiting the gym are the complimentary bottles of water and fruit.Transfer time (by town car) from the airport is around 25-30 minutes. The hotel is located perfectly - the California cable car line is only a short walk from the hotel, with Union Square around a 10 minute walk. Also nearby is Chinatown - an excellent experience with some superb restaurants. We never ate at the hotel as we were more often out but I can recommend the local Deli's for breakfast.The Mandarin Oriental San Francisco is not the cheapest hotel by any means but if you want a really special experience where you are made to feel like a king and queen then this is the hotel for you. San Fran is a fantastic city and if I ever get the opportunity to go back I will make sure I am staying at the Mandarin.	
